    <item>
      <title>Mapping the Flood Extent of the Okavango Delta in R</title>
      <link>https://daviddhofmann.github.io/post/floodmapping/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 18 Dec 2023 18:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://daviddhofmann.github.io/post/floodmapping/</guid>
      <description>The Okavango Delta is one of the world&amp;rsquo;s most pristine ecosystems, hosting a large diversity of animal and plant species. It represents the planet&amp;rsquo;s largest inland delta and is characterized by significant seasonal fluctuations of its flood extent. In this blog post, I will introduce you to a simple, yet effective approach to remote sense the Delta&amp;rsquo;s flood extent using MODIS satellite imagery and the &lt;code&gt;floodmapr&lt;/code&gt; R-package.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Bat-Eared Fox (Otocyon megalotis)</title>
      <link>https://daviddhofmann.github.io/animals/batearedfox/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 09 Sep 2023 09:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://daviddhofmann.github.io/animals/batearedfox/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The bat-eared fox (&lt;em&gt;Otocyon megalotis&lt;/em&gt;) is a medium-sized canid that calls&#xA;sub-Saharan Africa its home. Adult individuals typically weigh less than 6 kg&#xA;and measure between 70 and 90 cm from nose to tail. Within the canid family,&#xA;the bat-eared fox stands alone as the sole representative of the genus&#xA;&lt;em&gt;Otocyon&lt;/em&gt;. Its closest relatives include domestic dogs, wolves and foxes.&#xA;Thanks to its eponymous and extraordinary set of ears, however, the bat-eared&#xA;fox cannot be mistaken for any other species (Figure 1).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>A Fair Share to De-Snare</title>
      <link>https://daviddhofmann.github.io/post/snareddogs/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 17 Aug 2022 12:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://daviddhofmann.github.io/post/snareddogs/</guid>
      <description>During my last season of field work in Botswana, we encountered a pack of wild dogs where some individuals carried a wire snare around their neck. Luckily, with the aid of a wildlife veterinarian, we were able to remove the snares.</description>
